ertidal macroinvertebrates, seaweeds, and seagrasses. Rather than prescribing standard protocols or procedures, the authors break down the decision-making process into various elements so investigators can become aware of the advantages and disadvantages of choosing a particular method or approach. Chapters discuss topics such as site selection, field sampling layouts and designs, selection of sampling units, nondestructive and destructive methods of quantifying abundance, and methods for measuring age, growth rates, size, structure, and reproductive condition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEnvironmental monitoringxMethodology. 0aIntertidal ecologyxResearchxMethodology. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh  abrackish.  aclimate change.  acoastline.  aearth sciences.  aecology.  aenvironment.  aenvironmentalism.  afield sampling layouts.  afieldwork.  aglobal warming.  agrowth rates.  aintertidal macroinvertebrates.  aintertidal zone.  aintertidal.  amacroinvertebrates.  amarine environment.  anature.  anonfiction.  aocean health.  aocean plants.  aocean.  aoceanography.  aquantifying abundance.  areproductive condition.  asampling units.  ascience.  aseagrasses.  aseaweeds.  ashoreline.  asite selection.  awater plants.1 aAmbrose, Richard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aDethier, Megan N., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024728440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093271540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520932715423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520932715/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of 